Date: 5/11/1852
Source: Daily Southern Cross
Author:
Vol / Page: 2
Edition:
Quote: The progress made at the Coromandel diggings has, until within the last eight and forty hours been suggestive rather of the possibility of hidden wealth, than illustrative of its speedy attainment; for although minute samples of gold had been obtained from every panful of washed soil, still it was so insignificant in quantity as to lead the impatient to imagine that little short of failure would be the result.
Notes:

Date: 10/11/1898
Source: Otago Witness
Author:
Vol / Page: 18
Edition:
Quote: Moonlight went over the hill, and found what is known as Moonlight Creek, and your humble servant went up the river on this side until I got above the canyon, where I found what was known as Sutherland's Beach, getting 13oz out of the first two pansful I washed out.
Notes:

Date: 9/11/1852
Source: NZ Government Gazette
Author:
Vol / Page: V/26/165
Edition:
Quote:  ... they reached a bend of the Creek, where they found Ring's party at work, sinking into the bed of it, the water having been turned off a short distance above. Your Committee had a quantity of the stuff taken out of this hole, and washed ..., and every panful of it produced a few specks of gold.
Notes:  (Report of Sub-Committee on Recent Gold Discovery in the Coromandel District) V

